body:
@jreback previously only one date format was supported (and no datetime formats). But there was a special note `Not all SAS date formats are supported`. So is it a bug then?.)
>Do users need to do anything differently? (e.g. convert_dates will just happen)?

`convert_dates=True` by default and it cannot be controlled in `read_sas` (as for now). So some columns treated earlier as numeric ones can become datetime columns.

> What I am trying to understand, are SAS fields 'tagged' as datetime in any way? Or do we just try to convert all numeric columns???

@jreback The fields are tagged, but I am not aware of a canonical listing of what values the tags are allowed to take.  This PR adds a bunch of tags to the list recognized as datetime/date/time columns.

> Do you have some more example files that we can add for testing? (IOW w/o some of these more common formats)?

I branched  [sas7bdat](https://bitbucket.org/jaredhobbs/sas7bdat) because I needed to speed up CSV conversion of some massive files.  If nothing else, the test cases I put together should all be applicable here.

@Winand A format that I recently encountered in the wild that I don't see in the new list is "YYMMDDN".  A date that _should_ be 2017-02-16 is showing up as 20866.0, so it looks like the format is "days elapsed since 1960-01-01".  Unfortunately I can't share the file this came from.

@Winand 
> only date and datetime formats are supported. Time columns are left as is - numeric values. Afaik, there's no special dtype for time, is there?

My mistake.  I was thinking of the upstream version, which converts time columns to datetime.time objects.

@jreback 
I just looked quickly through my tests and don't see any datetime formats in the public-domain files.  Those came from [here](http://www.principlesofeconometrics.com/sas.htm) and [here](https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/tutorials/dietary/downloads/downloads.htm).  I'll take a closer look and see if there is anything else in here I can contribute.
